  {t:'The Design of the Unix Operating System',a:'Maurice Bach',n:'The Unix internals book. Primary source of Unix.',primary:true},
  {t:'Computer Networks',a:'Tanenbaum & Wetherall',n:'Layer-by-layer networking depth.'},
],lec:[
  {t:'Arpaci-Dusseau: OSTEP (free PDF)',u:'https://pages.cs.wisc.edu/~remzi/OSTEP/',type:'book-free'},
  {t:'CMU 15-213: Introduction to Computer Systems',u:'https://www.cs.cmu.edu/~213/',type:'course'},
]},

embedded_sys:{tier:4,cat:'hw',label:'Embedded Systems & Microcontrollers',
desc:'Microcontroller architecture (ARM Cortex-M series), bare-metal C, interrupt handlers, DMA, UART/SPI/I2C/CAN protocols, RTOS concepts (FreeRTOS, Zephyr), real-time scheduling theory, power management. Entirely homelab-feasible with an STM32 or Raspberry Pi Pico ($4–$15).',
figures:'Mead & Conway (VLSI methodology), Conway (microprocessor design)',
jonathan:'An STM32F4 board costs $10. You can build a full bare-metal system, implement your own scheduler, and get signals from real sensors. This is the homelab sweet spot.',
